msDesc.head: A treatise on preaching and several medical texts

foliation.p: Foliated in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each front endleaf, the first recto of each quire in Part 2 and the first leaf of Part 3.
foliation.note: There are several different medieval and modern foliation schemas present in this manuscript. For the production of this online CUDL record, the modern pencil foliation ff. i-iv + 1-88 was extended as ff. [89]-[206] + [v]-[viii], with all numbers assigned during the production of this electronic record being enclosed in [square brackets].
Please note that M. R. James created and used a different foliation schema in the preparation of his Catalogue record, with the foliation sequence restarting at f. 1 in each Part.

foliation.p: Foliated in ink in typical medieval forms of Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each recto of ff. iii recto - 12v. This medieval sequence is written in large numbers in a light brown ink and is not a close visual match for any of the other medieval foliation sequences present in the volume. This sequence demonstrates that Parts 1 and 2 have been together since the medieval period.

Foliated in ink in typical medieval forms of Hindu-Arabic numerals in the lower outer corner of each recto of ff. iv recto - 27v. This medieval sequence is written in a dark brown ink and is not a close visual match for any of the other medieval foliation sequences present in the volume. This sequence demonstrates that Parts 1 and 2 have been together since the medieval period.

Foliated in ink in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each recto of ff. 88-[89]. This medieval sequence is written in a dark brown ink and is not a close visual match for any of the other medieval foliation sequences present in the volume.

Foliated in ink in the typical medieval forms of Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each recto of ff. [116] recto - [206] verso. This medieval sequence is written in a dark brown ink and is not a close visual match for any of the other medieval foliation sequences present in the volume. There are several mistakes in this foliation sequence.

binding.p: Medieval binding, perhaps 14th century. Rebacked and repaired after 1908.

Covers are undecorated whitened skin over wood boards with bevelled edges. Remains of a hook-and-catch type fastening visible as damage in the centre of the fore edge of each board. Spine rebacked in light brown leather; five raised bands visible and two half bands tangible. No head or tail bands or tabs visible. Two small printed paper labels fixed to the spine, one '413' and the other '407' for the current shelfmark. Inner faces of both boards visible; front pastedown lifted and now f. i, back pastedown gone, but offset on the turn in suggests that it was another leaf of the booklet used for the endleaves (ff. i-iv and [v]-[viii]. Front board repaired or recycled in the middle ages as the board has five lacing channels along the fore edge of its inner face, all with signs of use, suggesting that the board was rotated 180° and then replaced in its current position.
Goville and Caius College bookplate on f. i recto and iv verso.

Two titles in ink in an early modern hand on the left cover, both badly rubbed. The first, 'Tract pro Con...uris; the second, 'Medicinalia permulsa'. 'Dietarum otonis' in ink on the right cover in a medieval hand.

history.acquisition: No acquisition information, but part of the Gonville and Caius Library by 1600, when it was recorded as no. 100 in the Ecloga Oxonio-Cantabrigiensis by Thomas James (1600).

recordHist.source: This catalogue entry draws on M. R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the manuscripts in the library of Gonville and Caius College, 3 vols (Cambridge, 1908) and unpublished research by Dr Debby Banham on the medical contents of the volume and in particular the content of Part 4.

note.p: Erased note, perhaps an ownership inscription on f. iv verso. The inscription is partially legible under U.V. light and includes the words 'johannes stukey magistri 1439'. A possible candidate for the author of the inscription is a medieval author known as 'John Meare' (or Mears), of Stukey, but his biographical details are not fully established. In his history of the city of Norwich, Francis Blomfield records a monk of Norwich Cathedral Priory: 'John Meare, or Mears, of Stukey, [...] D. D. of the University of Oxford, [who] flourished in the reign of King Edward IV. He wrote a book of sermons; and four books on the Master of the Sentences, which were preserved in the library of his monastery.' Johannes Stukey is also listed in Emden's A Biographical Register of the University of Oxford p. 1809, and is described as an author with theological works attributed to him, but Emden fixes that Stukey with dates of activity in the first half of the 14th century. Further work is needed to establish the context of the Johannes Stukey Johannes Stukey inscription in this manuscript.

p.seg: Ruled very fainly in leadpoint, usually just frame, sometimes frame and lines. Ruled in single-column format, typically 36 lines to the page and written below top line, but mise-en-page treated informally in this Part. Upper, outer, and inner margins all used for annotations. Titles of the works contained in this Part are unusually difficult to determine, but are frequently found in small enclosed labels in the upper margin of the leaf following the beginning of the text.

handNote.p: Written in a very informal cursiva, closest in style to cursiva antiquior.

decoNote.p: Occasional plain initials at the beginning of a new text, usually black, sometimes red.
